Passenger Satisfaction Prediction¶

Context¶

This problem statement is based on the Shinkansen Bullet Train in Japan, and passengers experience with that mode of travel. This machine-learning exercise aims to determine the relative importance of each parameter with regard to their contribution to the passengers overall travel experience.

Goal¶

The goal of the problem is to predict whether a passenger was satisfied or not considering his/her overall experience of traveling on the Shinkansen Bullet Train. We would also like to understand which parameters play an important role in swaying passenger feedback towards a positive scale.

DataSet¶

The dataset contains a random sample of individuals who travelled on this train. There are two datasets for this problem: Travel data and Survey data.

  • Travel data: Information related to passengers and attributes related to the Shinkansen train, in which they traveled.
  • Survey data: Aggregated data of surveys indicating the post-service experience including their "Overall Experience". (Passengers were later asked to provide their feedback on various parameters related to the travel along with their overall experience.)

Data Description¶

  • ID - The unique ID of the passenger
  • Gender - The gender of the passenger: "Male", "Female"
  • Customer_Type - Loyalty type of the passenger: "Loyal Customer" , "Disloyal Customer"
  • Age - The age of the passenger
  • Type_Travel - Purpose of travel for the passenger: "Personal Travel", "Business Travel"
  • Travel_Class - The train class that the passenger traveled in: "Business", "Eco"
  • Travel_Distance - The distance traveled by the passenger
  • Departure_Delay_in_Mins - The delay (in minutes) in train departure
  • Arrival_Delay_in_Mins - The delay (in minutes) in train arrival

# Function to plot the boxplot and histogram of a feature

def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(10, 5), kde=False): 
    
    f2, (ax_boxplot, ax_hist) = plt.subplots(
        nrows = 2,      # Number of rows of the subplot
        sharex = True,  # x-axis will be shared among the two subplots
        gridspec_kw = {"height_ratios": (0.2, 0.8)},
        figsize = figsize,
    ) 

    # the mean value of the column is displayed using a star
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_boxplot, showmeans=True, color="lightgreen")  

    # Histogram
    sns.histplot(data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist) 

    # show mean with a green dotted line 
    ax_hist.axvline(data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--")
    
    # show median with a black solid line
    ax_hist.axvline(data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-")

# Function to plot labeled barplots

def labeled_barplot(data, feature):

    # create a new figure that has a width proportional to the number of bars that we want to show    
    plt.figure(figsize=(data[feature].nunique() + 1, 5)) 
    
    plt.xticks(rotation = 90)
    
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data = data,
        x = feature,
        palette = "Paired",
        order = data[feature].value_counts().index[:].sort_values(),
    )

    for patch in ax.patches:

        x = patch.get_x() + patch.get_width() / 2 
        y = patch.get_height()

        ax.text(x, y, y, ha='center', va='bottom')

    plt.show()  # show the plot

Data Preprocessing¶

In [ ]:
# there are some "categorical" and some "numerical" columns in this dataset:
categorical_columns   = ['Gender', 'Customer_Type', 'Type_Travel', 'Travel_Class', 'Seat_Class']
numerical_columns     = ['ID', 'Age', 'Travel_Distance', 'Departure_Delay_in_Mins', 'Arrival_Delay_in_Mins']
likert_scale_columns1 = ["Seat_Comfort", "Arrival_Time_Convenient", "Catering", "Onboard_Wifi_Service", 
                        "Onboard_Entertainment", "Online_Support", "Ease_of_Online_Booking", "Onboard_Service", "Legroom", 
                        "Baggage_Handling", "CheckIn_Service", "Cleanliness", "Online_Boarding"]
likert_scale_columns2 = ["Platform_Location"]
In [ ]:
def data_preprocessing(data):
  
  ###################  Missing Value Imputation  ###################

  ## Filling Missing values in categorical columns and likert-scale columns with "the most frequent value" in those columns.
  for column in categorical_columns + likert_scale_columns1 + likert_scale_columns2:
      data[column].fillna(value = data[column].mode()[0], inplace=True)
  
  ## Filling Missing values in numerical columns with "the mean" in those columns.
  for column in numerical_columns:
      data[column].fillna(value=data[column].mean(), inplace=True)


  ###################  Encoding Categorical Columns  ###################

  ### Do one hot encoding for categorical variables
  encoded_cols = pd.get_dummies(data[categorical_columns], prefix = categorical_columns)
  data = pd.concat([data, encoded_cols], axis=1)         # concatenate the encoded columns with the original dataframe
  data.drop(categorical_columns, axis=1, inplace=True)   # drop the original categorical columns
  

  ###################  Encoding Likert Scale Columns  ###################

  mapping1 = {'Extremely Poor': 1,    'Poor': 2,         'Acceptable': 3, 'Needs Improvement': 4, 'Good': 5,       'Excellent': 6      }
  mapping2 = {'Very Inconvenient': 1, 'Inconvenient': 2, 'Manageable': 3, 'Needs Improvement': 4, 'Convenient': 5, 'Very Convenient': 6}   

  # Mapping Lekert scale texts to ordinal numbers
  ordinal_columns1 = data[likert_scale_columns1].applymap(lambda x: mapping1.get(x))
  ordinal_columns2 = data[likert_scale_columns2].applymap(lambda x: mapping2.get(x))

  # Dropping Likert-scale columns
  data = data.drop(likert_scale_columns1, axis = 1)
  data = data.drop(likert_scale_columns2, axis = 1)

  # Change column types from float to int
  for col in ordinal_columns1.columns:
    ordinal_columns1[col] = ordinal_columns1[col].astype(int)
  for col in ordinal_columns2.columns:
    ordinal_columns2[col] = ordinal_columns2[col].astype(int)

  # Adding Mapped columns (Containing Ordinal numbers instead of Likert Scale texts)
  data = pd.concat([data, ordinal_columns1], axis=1)
  data = pd.concat([data, ordinal_columns2], axis=1)

  return data

# Creating metric function 
def metrics_score(actual, predicted):

    print(classification_report(actual, predicted, digits=4))

    plt.figure(figsize=(4,3))
    
    sns.heatmap(confusion_matrix(actual, predicted), 
                xticklabels=['False', 'True'], 
                yticklabels=['False', 'True'], 
                annot=True, 
                fmt='.2f')
    
    plt.ylabel('Actual')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()

Hyperparameter Tuning

In [ ]:
# Hyperparameter tuning for X_train/X_eval data
model_xgb3 = xgb.XGBClassifier(objective='binary:logistic', random_state=42)

# Define the hyperparameter grid
param_grid = {
    'max_depth': [5, 10, 15],
    'learning_rate': [0.1, 0.01, 0.001],
    'n_estimators': [50, 100, 200],
}

# Perform grid search cross-validation
grid_search = GridSearchCV(
    model_xgb3, param_grid=param_grid, cv=5, scoring='accuracy', n_jobs=-1
)
grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train, verbose = 2)

# Print the best hyperparameters and accuracy score
print("Best hyperparameters:", grid_search.best_params_)
print("Accuracy:", grid_search.best_score_)

# Evaluate the best model on the testing data
best_model = grid_search.best_estimator_
y_pred_xgb3 = best_model.predict(X_test)
metrics_score(y_test, y_pred_xgb3)

Conclusion¶

  • Many Models were tested including:
    • Logistic Regression,
    • Decision Tree,
    • Random Forest,
    • XGBoost
    • Support Vector Machine,
    • Neural Network
  • The best results were achieved using **XGBoost** algorithm with these parameters: learning_rate: 0.1, max_depth: 10, n_estimators: 200

  • The best results after XGBoost was earned using **Random Forest** model.
